# Development Lifecycle

## Stages

```
IDEA → DRAFT → REFINE → IMPLEMENT → PR → (RELEASE)
```

### Draft
A raw idea or bug report added with `/draft`. No planning required.
Spec file created in `docs/specs/backlog/`. Minimal content — just enough to capture the idea.

### Refine
Refinement depth scales with a complexity triage (trivial / small / medium / large — judged by scope, novelty, risk, and ambiguity, no hard limits). Trivial specs are fast-tracked through a single combined planning pass that escalates itself if it finds hidden complexity; small, medium, and large specs go through the full Requirements Engineer + Tech Planner iteration until the spec meets the **Definition of Ready**. Larger and more critical specs get more iteration rounds, more clarifying questions, and a higher model/effort tier (see `decisions.md` → Sizing defaults); the tech-planner also decides each ticket's implementation/test tier, recorded in the spec's `routing:` block.
Triggered with `/refine {id}`. Spec moves to `docs/specs/ready/` when DoR is satisfied.

### Implement
Tests are written first (isolated context, spec-only), then code is implemented subtask by subtask.
Each subtask gets its own commit. Run with `/implement {id}`.
Progress is checkpointed — use `/resume` after any interruption.

### PR
CI runs first (lint + typecheck + tests + security). Claude waits for CI, then scales the reviews
to the diff: small low-risk diffs get one combined review; anything touching security-sensitive
files (auth, crypto, deps, input handling, …) always gets the dedicated security review, plus code
review and optionally architect review. All findings are fixed before merge.
Run with `/pr`. Claude auto-merges after all reviews pass.

### Release
Version bump, CHANGELOG update, git tag, push. CI publishes the release.
Run with `/release patch|minor|major`.

